%claude:
A compiler is a critical piece of the development toolchain:
every C program in this book series---the \book{Shell}, the
\book{Builder}, the \book{Kernel}---was compiled by a C compiler
before it could run. Understanding how that translation works
removes a layer of mystery and makes you a more effective
programmer, whether you are debugging a miscompilation,
writing performance-sensitive code, or simply trying to
understand what the machine actually executes.

%claude:
Compilers are also where many important ideas in computer science
come together: formal grammars and parsing, type systems, graph
algorithms for register allocation, and low-level code generation.
These techniques are not confined to compilers---they appear in
linters, code formatters, IDEs, query engines, and static analysis
tools. Understanding a real compiler gives you a foundation
for all of these.

%claude:
The industry certainly takes compilers seriously: Google, Apple,
and others invest heavily in LLVM and GCC, and compiler
improvements directly translate into faster software for
millions of users. Even in the age of AI coding assistants,
understanding compilation matters---an LLM can generate C code,
but only a compiler can tell you whether it is well-typed,
and only a compiler can turn it into instructions the processor
can execute.

Here are a few questions I hope this book will answer:
\begin{itemize}

\item How does a compiler parse a complex programming language?
\n Lexing, (preprocessing), parsing

\item How does a compiler manage the scope of variables,
structures, enumerations, or typedefs?
\l forward declaration, implicit declaration, nested scopes and shadowing, 
\n symbol table

\item How does a typechecker work?

\item How does a compiler translate 
conditionals, loops, and other control-flow constructs
in basic assembly jumps?
%codegen: labelize

\item How does a compiler translate a switch?

\item How does a compiler convert arbitrary complex expressions 
into simpler assembly instructions using a small set of registers?
%codegen: linearize

\item How does a function pass arguments to another function?
Are registers used? Is the stack used? How does a function communicate 
its return value to the caller?
%codegen: frameize

\item What are simple useful optimizations?

% aligns, offsets, structs, size

\end{itemize}

