\chapter{Overview}
%******************************************************************************

%trans:
%claude:
Before showing the source code of [[5c]] in the following chapters,
I first give an overview in this chapter
of the general principles of a compiler,
of its command-line interface,
and of the input and output formats.
%
I also define terms and more generally give the background necessary
to understand the code I will show later.

\section{Compiler principles}

% from high level to low level (asm).

% Many books on compiler. I will be short here.

% FIGURE with different steps.
% and group some boxes in frontend vs backend

% principles of frontend and backend.
% (We will focus mostly on the backend)

%claude:
A compiler translates a high-level language into a low-level one.
In the case of [[5c]], the input is C and the output is ARM
assembly (in \plan's AST-based object format).
%
There are many books on compiler construction---the ``Dragon
Book''~\cite{dragon-book}, Appel's ``Modern Compiler
Implementation''~\cite{appel}, and others.
I will be brief here and focus on the aspects most relevant
to understanding [[5c]].

%claude:
The compiler lineage starts with Fortran (John Backus,
{\sc ibm}, 1957)---the first {\em optimizing} compiler,
which proved that a high-level language could produce code
competitive with hand-written assembly. C (Dennis Ritchie,
1972) was the first language whose compiler was good
enough to write an operating system kernel in. {\sc gnu}'s
[[gcc]] (Richard Stallman, 1987) became the dominant open
source compiler for two decades. {\sc llvm} (Chris
Lattner, 2003) offered a modular architecture that made
it easy to add new frontends (Clang for C/C\texttt{++},
Rust, Swift) and new backends (ARM, x86, RISC-V, WebAssembly),
and is now the foundation of most non-{\sc gnu} toolchains.
[[5c]] sits at the minimal end of this spectrum: around
10\,000 lines of C, readable end-to-end, with none of the
framework machinery that makes [[gcc]] or {\sc llvm}
powerful but enormous.

%claude:
Compilers are traditionally divided into a {\em frontend}
(parsing and analysis) and a {\em backend} (code generation
and optimization). The following diagram shows the main
phases of a typical compiler:

%claude:
\begin{verbatim}
  Source    Lexer    Parser     Checker     Code Gen   Optimizer
    |         |        |          |            |          |
    v         v        v          v            v          v
  text --> tokens --> AST --> typed AST --> assembly --> assembly
                                              (opt)
          <--- Frontend --->              <--- Backend --->
\end{verbatim}

%claude:
[[5c]] follows this structure, though it blurs some boundaries:
parsing and code generation are interleaved (each function is
compiled immediately after parsing), and there is no separate
intermediate representation between the AST and the assembly
instruction list.

\subsection{Frontend}

% Frontend is classic and present in other books like Assembler,
% or Make, or Shell.
% Lexing (regexps), (preprocessing), parsing (grammar), AST.
% (even though 5c does a lot in parsing; does not separate concern so well).
% Tracking position for good error reports.

%claude:
The frontend transforms source text into a structured
representation. It consists of three phases:
{\em lexing} (breaking text into tokens), {\em preprocessing}
(handling [[#include]], [[#define]], and [[#ifdef]]),
and {\em parsing} (building an abstract syntax tree from
the token stream according to C's grammar).
%
If you have read the \book{Assembler} or \book{Shell},
you have already seen all three phases---the same techniques
(hand-written lexer, macro expansion, grammar-driven parsing)
appear in [[5c]], applied to the more complex syntax of C.

%claude:
Modern compilers overwhelmingly use hand-written
recursive-descent parsers rather than generated ones:
{\sc gcc} moved from [[yacc]] to hand-written in~2004
for better error recovery, Clang was always
hand-written, and Rust, Go, and Swift followed suit.
[[5c]] is an exception---it still uses [[yacc]], which
keeps the grammar readable but limits error-message
quality.

\subsection{Scope resolution}
% Resolving, naming.

% C has nested blocks, and can shadow variables.
% Can also forward decls.
% C has also type aliases (typedefs). Lots of names.
% Have even ambiguity between typedef and var.
% When see an identifier, hard to know to what it refers too
% (a typedef? defined in which scope? a variable? in which scope? an enum?
% in which scope?)
% Goal of naming is to associate to the use of an entity the right
% definition.

%claude:
C has nested blocks, and a variable in an inner block can
shadow a variable of the same name in an outer block. C also
has type aliases ([[typedef]]), structure tags, enumeration
constants, and labels---all in partially overlapping namespaces.
The goal of scope resolution is to associate each {\em use}
of a name with the correct {\em definition}. This is done
through the symbol table, which tracks the current scope
and allows declarations to be pushed and popped as the
compiler enters and exits blocks.

\subsection{Use/def checking}

% For many things! related to naming.
% 3 important checks: use-of-undefined, redefined, unused.

% for many entities:
%  - labels
%  - locals
% could also for:
%  - globals
%  - function defs
%  - typedefs
%  - struct defs
%  - enums.

%claude:
Closely related to scope resolution, use/def checking
catches three kinds of errors: {\em use of undefined}
entities (referencing a variable that was never declared),
{\em redefinition} (declaring the same name twice in the
same scope), and {\em unused} definitions (declaring
something that is never referenced). [[5c]] performs
these checks for labels, local variables, and parameters,
and additionally includes dataflow checks for variables
that are set but never used.

\subsection{Type checking}

% A more unusual part of frontend is typechecking! and annotate AST
% with types. C not a dynamic language.

% - types! typechecking! (5c even adds some simple dataflow checks!)
%   so can type check arguments vs parameters, their numbers, array access,
%   field access, more restricted register indexing (xxx) -> *xxx but only
%   if makes sense.
%   (still have lots of room to improve even more, C could be more typed!
%    see rust, and ocaml).

% type annotating also.

% lvalue/rvalue annotating here?

%claude:
Since C is a statically typed language, the compiler must
verify that operations are applied to compatible types: that
function arguments match parameters, that array indices are
integers, that pointer dereferences apply to pointers, and
so on. The type checker also annotates each AST node with
its type, which the backend needs to generate correctly
sized instructions (a [[char]] move vs.\ a [[long]] move,
integer vs.\ floating-point arithmetic).
%
The type checker also classifies expressions as {\em lvalues}
(locations that can be assigned to) or {\em rvalues}
(values that can only be read), which determines what
operations are legal on each expression.

%claude:
C's type system is relatively weak: no generics, no sum
types, [[void*]] as a universal escape hatch, and
implicit integer conversions that silently lose data.
Modern languages push the type checker much further:
Rust's {\em borrow checker} tracks ownership and
lifetimes at compile time to prevent use-after-free
without a garbage collector; OCaml's {\em algebraic
types} make unhandled cases a compile error; Haskell's
{\em type classes} express abstractions the C type
system cannot even name. The trade-off is the familiar
``worse is better'' question: C's weak types are simpler
and more permissive, letting more bugs through but also
letting more code compile without fighting the type
checker.

\subsection{Backend}

% Assembly is essentially:
%  - simple arith with registers and memory instructions
%  - labels and jmps
%  - simple stack (when you have to manually handle locals, params, and calls)
%  - simple data structure, bytes
% The goal of the C compiler is to translate in this simpler language
% the more complex construct of C.

%interactively see the asm generated by gcc
%https://godbolt.org/

%https://kristerw.blogspot.com/2017/08/the-structure-of-gcc-back-end.html

%claude:
The backend's job is to translate the typed AST into assembly
instructions. Assembly is a much simpler language than C:
arithmetic on registers, memory loads and stores, labels
and jumps, and a manually managed stack. The compiler must
bridge the gap between C's structured constructs and this
flat instruction sequence. This bridge can be understood
as three translations, which I call {\em labelization},
{\em linearization}, and {\em frameization}.

\subsection{Labelization and control-flow lowering}

% - statements, more structured forms than jmp.

%claude:
C has structured control flow: [[if]]/[[else]], [[while]],
[[for]], [[switch]], [[break]], [[continue]], [[return]].
Assembly has only labels and conditional/unconditional jumps.
{\em Labelization} is the translation from one to the other:
an [[if(cond) A else B]] becomes a conditional branch past
[[A]] to [[B]], with a label at the join point. A [[while]]
loop becomes a backward jump to the condition test.

%yoann: concrete diagram example of C on left and assembly on right
%claude:
\begin{verbatim}
  C code                    ARM assembly
  ------                    ------------
  if(x > 0)                    CMP   x, $0
      y = 1;                   BLE   L1
  else                         MOVW  $1, y
      y = 2;                   B     L2
                            L1:
                               MOVW  $2, y
                            L2:
\end{verbatim}

\subsection{Linearization and three-address code}
% registerization

% - expression like x+y*z decomposed into multi mov, add, etc. Fortran!
% - same for data, complex decomposed into smaller bytes, with symbolic names
%   for subparts, e.g. fields.

%claude:
C expressions can be arbitrarily nested: [[x + y * z - f(a, b)]].
Assembly instructions operate on at most two or three registers
at a time. {\em Linearization} decomposes complex expressions
into a sequence of simple instructions, allocating temporary
registers for intermediate results. For example, [[x + y * z]]
becomes: load [[y]] into a register, multiply by [[z]], add [[x]].
%
The same applies to data: a C struct with nested fields is
decomposed into byte-level accesses at computed offsets.

%yoann: concrete diagram example of C on left and assembly on right
%claude:
\begin{verbatim}
  C code                    ARM assembly
  ------                    ------------
  z = x + y * 3;               MOVW  y, R0
                                MOVW  $3, R1
                                MUL   R1, R0       // R0 = y * 3
                                MOVW  x, R1
                                ADD   R1, R0       // R0 = x + y*3
                                MOVW  R0, z
\end{verbatim}

\subsection{Instruction selection}

%claude:
After linearization decomposes expressions into simple
operations (load, add, multiply, store), the compiler
must choose which {\em machine instructions} implement
each operation. This is {\em instruction selection}, and
it is less trivial than it sounds: ARM offers many ways
to compute the same result. A multiply by~4 can be a
shift left by~2. An add of a small constant can use an
immediate operand instead of loading the constant into a
register first. A load followed by an add can sometimes
be combined into a single load-with-offset instruction.
Choosing the best instruction (or sequence) for each
operation is what separates good generated code from
mediocre.

%claude:
Classical compiler textbooks describe {\em tree pattern
matching} (BURG, Aho and Johnson 1976): the compiler
tiles each expression tree with instruction patterns and
picks the minimum-cost tiling. {\sc gcc} and {\sc llvm}
use elaborate machine-description files that
automatically generate instruction selectors from
declarative rules. [[5c]] uses a simpler approach:
hand-written C code that walks the AST and emits
instructions directly, with ad hoc rules for the special
cases (shift-for-multiply, immediate folding, combined
addressing modes). This is less systematic but far easier
to read, and the ARM's relatively regular instruction set
means the number of special cases stays manageable.

\subsection{Frameization and stack-frame layout}

% - parameters, arguments, locals, more structured forms than just plain stack
% => see codegen: tag

%claude:
C has function parameters, local variables, and return values.
Assembly has only the stack pointer and registers. {\em Frameization}
is the mapping between the two: the compiler assigns each local
variable and parameter an offset within the function's {\em stack
frame}, generates code to set up the frame on entry (adjusting
the stack pointer), and tears it down on exit. The
{\em calling convention} defines which registers hold arguments,
where the return value goes, and which registers must be saved
and restored across calls.

%claude:
Calling conventions vary across architectures and
operating systems. ARM's {\sc aapcs} (ARM Architecture
Procedure Call Standard) puts the first four arguments
in [[R0]]--[[R3]] and the rest on the stack; x86-64
System~V (Linux, macOS) uses six registers; Windows x64
uses four different registers. \plan defines its own
convention ([[R0]] for first argument and return value,
described in \book{Libcore}'s assembly crash course).
Getting the calling convention wrong produces bugs that
are extraordinarily hard to diagnose: the callee reads
its arguments from the wrong registers, and the program
crashes far from the actual error.

%yoann: concrete diagram example of C on left and assembly on right
%claude:
\begin{verbatim}
  C code                    ARM assembly
  ------                    ------------
  int add(int a, int b) {      TEXT add+0(SB), $8   // 8 bytes for locals
      int sum;                 MOVW a+0(FP), R0     // param a at FP+0
      sum = a + b;             MOVW b+4(FP), R1     // param b at FP+4
      return sum;              ADD  R1, R0
  }                            MOVW R0, sum-4(SP)   // local at SP-4
                               MOVW R0, .ret+0(FP)  // return value
                               RET
\end{verbatim}

\subsection{Optimizations}

%claude:
After generating assembly, the compiler can improve it.
[[5c]] performs two levels of optimization: {\em AST-level}
transformations (constant folding, strength reduction,
algebraic simplification) and {\em assembly-level}
optimizations (register allocation across basic blocks,
and peephole optimization to eliminate redundant instructions).
These are modest compared to what GCC or LLVM do, but
they are effective and easy to understand.

%claude:
To put [[5c]]'s modest optimization in perspective:
{\sc gcc} runs roughly 200 optimization passes over its
{\sc ir}, {\sc llvm} runs about 100, and [[5c]] runs
about 10---a difference that reflects the ``worse is
better'' trade-off between peak code quality and compiler
simplicity.

\subsection{Intermediate representations and SSA}

%claude:
Most modern compilers do not translate directly from AST
to assembly. Instead, they lower the AST into an
{\em intermediate representation} ({\sc ir})---a language
simpler than C but richer than assembly---and perform
most optimizations there. {\sc gcc} has two {\sc ir}s:
{\sc gimple} (a simplified C-like tree) and {\sc rtl}
(register transfer language, close to assembly). {\sc
llvm}'s {\sc ir} is a single, well-defined language that
every frontend (Clang, Rust, Swift) compiles {\em into}
and every backend (ARM, x86, RISC-V) compiles {\em out
of}---which is what makes {\sc llvm} so modular.

%claude:
The most important property of modern {\sc ir}s is
{\em Static Single Assignment} ({\sc ssa}), formalized by
Cytron et al.\ in~1991: every variable is assigned
exactly once, and when a variable needs to be updated, a
new version is created. This sounds restrictive but it
makes dataflow analysis trivial---you can follow any
value back to its unique definition without searching
through a list of possible assignments---which enables
optimizations like constant propagation, dead-code
elimination, and common-subexpression elimination to be
expressed as simple graph walks. {\sc gcc} adopted {\sc
ssa} in~2004 ({\sc gcc}~4.0); {\sc llvm}'s {\sc ir} has
been {\sc ssa} from the start.

%claude:
[[5c]] has {\em neither} an {\sc ir} nor {\sc ssa}. It
goes straight from the AST to an assembly instruction
list, performing optimizations directly on both. This is
a deliberate ``worse is better'' simplification: it keeps
the compiler small (no {\sc ir} data structures to
maintain, no {\sc ssa} $\phi$-node insertion pass) at the
cost of missing the cross-function and global
optimizations that {\sc ssa}-based compilers excel at.
For the workloads \plan was designed for---operating
system code, command-line tools, compilers
themselves---the simpler approach was fast enough.

\subsection{Register allocation}

%claude:
One backend problem deserves its own mention because it
is the most studied optimization in compiler history.
The AST and linearization phase can use as many temporary
values as they want, but the {\sc cpu} has a finite
number of registers (16 on ARM, even fewer effectively
available after reserving [[SP]], [[LR]], [[PC]], and
[[SB]]). {\em Register allocation} is the mapping from
an unlimited set of virtual temporaries to this finite
set, with any overflow {\em spilled} to the stack.

%claude:
The classical formulation (Gregory Chaitin, {\sc ibm},
1981) models the problem as {\em graph coloring}: build
an {\em interference graph} whose nodes are temporaries
and whose edges connect temporaries that are live at the
same time; then color the graph with $k$ colors (one per
physical register). If a node cannot be colored, its
temporary is spilled. This produces excellent code but is
expensive (graph coloring is NP-complete in general,
though Chaitin's heuristic works well in practice).
{\em Linear scan} (Poletto and Sarkar, 1999) trades some
code quality for speed: it walks the instruction list
once, assigning registers in order of live-range start,
and is the algorithm of choice for {\sc jit} compilers
({\sc jvm} HotSpot's C1, V8's Crankshaft) where
compilation speed matters more than the last 5\% of code
quality. [[5c]] uses a simpler per-basic-block allocation
that is fast enough for the code sizes \plan targets.

\subsection{Peephole optimization}

%claude:
After instruction selection and register allocation, the
generated code still contains local inefficiencies: a
value loaded into a register and then immediately moved
to another (the move is redundant); a store followed by a
load of the same address (the load can be eliminated); a
conditional branch over a single instruction (on ARM, the
instruction can be conditionally executed instead). A
{\em peephole optimizer} fixes these by scanning a small
sliding window of consecutive instructions---the
``peephole'' through which it views the code, typically
2--5 instructions wide---and applying pattern-replacement
rules to clean up what it sees. The name comes from the
image of looking at a long instruction list through a
tiny hole: you can only see a few instructions at a time,
but that is enough to spot and fix local waste.

%claude:
The idea dates to William McKeeman (1965), and the
technique is one of the simplest in the compiler: each
rule is a pattern match (``if you see instruction~A
followed by instruction~B, replace with instruction~C''),
and the whole pass is a single loop over the instruction
list. Despite its simplicity, it produces significant
speedups by removing the overhead that the earlier, more
structured passes left behind. [[5c]]'s peephole
optimizer is under 200 lines and is one of the most
readable parts of the backend.

\subsection{Undefined behavior}

%claude:
C grants the compiler permission to assume that certain
operations {\em never happen}: signed integer overflow,
dereferencing a null pointer, reading an uninitialized
variable, shifting by more than the word width. These are
called {\em undefined behavior} ({\sc ub}), and the
language standard says the compiler may do ``anything''
when they occur---including silently removing the code
that would have detected them. Modern compilers exploit
this aggressively: if signed overflow is {\sc ub}, {\sc
gcc} and Clang can assume [[x + 1 > x]] is always true
and optimize away the overflow check, which sometimes
causes programs that ``worked'' with older compilers to
break silently under [[-O2]].

%claude:
[[5c]] is far less aggressive. It rarely exploits {\sc
ub} for optimization, which means it generates slower
code but produces fewer surprises---a trade-off the
\plan developers considered worthwhile for systems code
where predictability matters more than peak performance.
The {\sc ub} debate is one of the sharpest instances of
the ``worse is better'' tension in modern C: {\sc gcc}
and Clang choose ``better'' code at the cost of
surprising behavior; [[5c]] and \plan choose ``worse''
code that does what the programmer expected.

\subsection{Cross-compilation}

%claude:
Most compilers treat cross-compilation---generating code
for a different architecture than the one the compiler
runs on---as a special configuration that requires
passing flags like \verb+--target=arm-linux-gnueabihf+.
\plan's toolchain was designed for cross-compilation
{\em from the start}. The numbered-tool convention
([[5c]]/[[5a]]/[[5l]] for ARM, [[8c]]/[[8a]]/[[8l]] for
x86, [[6c]]/[[6a]]/[[6l]] for AMD64) makes every
compiler a cross-compiler by default: you compile ARM
code on an x86 machine by simply typing [[5c]] instead
of [[8c]], with no configuration, no sysroot, no target
triple. This is possible because the \plan compilers
carry no host dependencies---they read source, emit
object code, and link to \plan's own [[libc]],
regardless of which machine they happen to be running on.
The modern echo of this philosophy is Zig (Andrew Kelley,
2016), which ships its own C/C\texttt{++} cross-compiler
and has gained significant adoption precisely because
[[zig cc --target=aarch64-linux]] ``just works'' where
configuring a {\sc gcc} or Clang cross-toolchain is a
multi-step ordeal. \plan got this right in the~1990s.

\subsection{Bootstrapping}

%claude:
A compiler written in its own language faces a
chicken-and-egg problem: you need the compiler to compile
the compiler. The standard solution is {\em bootstrapping}:
start with a version compiled by some other means (a
previous version, a different compiler, or even a
hand-written translator), then use that to compile the
``real'' compiler from source. [[5c]] was bootstrapped
from earlier \plan compilers; Go's compiler, which
descends from the \plan toolchain, was famously rewritten
from C to Go in~2015 and bootstrapped via a chain:
Go~1.4 (the last C version) compiles Go~1.5 (the first
Go version), which compiles all subsequent versions.

%claude:
Ken Thompson's 1984 Turing Award lecture {\em
``Reflections on Trusting Trust''} revealed a deeper
problem with bootstrapping: a compiler can be modified to
insert a backdoor into any program it compiles---including
{\em future versions of itself}---so that the backdoor
propagates invisibly through every bootstrap, even if you
read every line of the compiler's source code and find
nothing suspicious. The attack is undetectable by source
inspection alone. The modern response is {\em diverse
double compilation} (David~A.\ Wheeler, 2009): compile the
compiler with two {\em independent} compilers and verify
that the outputs match, which catches any
compiler-specific backdoor because the two compilers
would have to contain the same one. Thompson's lecture
remains one of the most cited in computer science and is
a reminder that trust in software is always, ultimately,
trust in the toolchain.

\subsection{The most demanding reader of your code}

%claude:
A compiler reads your source code more carefully than any
human ever will. It checks every type, traces every
variable's lifetime, verifies that every function call
matches its declaration, detects unreachable code, warns
about uninitialized variables, and then transforms the
result into machine code you could not write by hand---all
in a fraction of a second. This is easy to take for
granted when the compiler is a black box behind [[make]],
but the rest of this book opens the box. What you will
find is that most of the compiler's complexity is
devoted not to the translation itself (which is
surprisingly mechanical) but to getting the {\em details}
right: the edge cases in type promotion, the interaction
between register allocation and spilling, the subtle
correctness requirements of instruction selection. The
compiler is, in effect, the programmer's most demanding
colleague---one who never gets tired, never skims, and
never lets an inconsistency pass.

