%claude:
[[5c]] compiles mostly ANSI C (C89), with a few \plan
extensions such as anonymous structs/unions and the
[[#pragma]] directives for format-string checking
and safe linking. 
%
C is a systems programming
language---pointers, explicit memory management, and
bit manipulation are central---and [[5c]] must handle
all of these, including the many dark corners of C's
syntax and semantics.

%\subsection{C innovations}

% innovation of C vs fortran/pascal/algol?
%  - pointer arithmetic? (but also a bad thing to have such wild pointers)
%    in some sense compilers such as Tiger are using pointers, but internally,
%    and C exposed them to the language while also providing some form
%    of algrebra around them (pointer arithmetic)
%  - simpler?
%  - bitfields? so can match more directly hardware specifics?
%  - in the end pretty good DSL for bit manipulations, &, |, ^, &=, <<, etc
%    are quite nice. See Linker.nw, Machine.nw, Assembler.nw.
%  - overloaded arithmetic for int/float/... ? (compared to OCaml)

%claude:
C's main innovation over Fortran and Pascal was {\em pointer
arithmetic}: pointers are first-class values that can be
incremented, compared, and subtracted. Other languages used
pointers internally, but C exposed them in the language with
an algebra around them ([[p + n]], [[p - q]], [[*p]]).
This gives C its power as a systems language, but it also
makes the compiler's job harder---there are no bounds checks
and wild pointers are easy to create.

%claude:
C also introduced a rich set of bit-manipulation operators
([[&]], [[|]], [[^]], [[<<]], [[>>]], and their assignment forms),
making it a natural Domain Specific Language (DSL) for the kind of
hardware-level code
that fills the \book{Linker}, \book{Emulator}, and \book{Assembler}.
Bitfields let structures map directly onto hardware register
layouts. 
%
Finally, C's overloaded arithmetic (the same [[+]] works
for [[int]], [[long]], [[float]], and [[double]]) simplifies
the surface language at the cost of a complex type-checker
that must insert the right coercions.

% Also lots of dark corners:
% https://people.eecs.berkeley.edu/~necula/cil/
% http://blog.robertelder.org/weird-c-syntax/

\section{Output object format}

% assembly ARM object code. Very close to ARM machine code.
% (can get asm generated via 5c -S)

% put code for helloworld.c generated code?

%claude:
Like [[5a]], [[5c]] generates object files in \plan's AST-based
format (not machine code). The output is essentially a serialized
list of assembly instructions---the same [<Prog>] structures
that the \book{Assembler} describes. The linker [[5l]] then
performs the actual machine code generation. You can use
[[5c -S]] to see the assembly in textual form.

\section{The ARM architecture}

% does not really need to understand much.
% Assembler of 5a abstracts a few things which is
% convenient (FP/SP, SB, generic MOVW, full integer constant, etc)

% Maybe a few instructions so can see how some simple C can be
% translated directly into ARM.
% x=1;
% MOVW $1, R0
% MOVW R0, x(SB)
% or
% MOVW R0, x+4(FP) or x-4(SP)

% y = &x
% MOVW $x(SB), R0
% MOVW R0, y(SB)

%claude:
You do not need deep knowledge of the ARM architecture to
read this book. The \plan assembler [[5a]] abstracts away
many hardware details with pseudo registers ([[FP]], [[SP]],
[[SB]]) and virtual instructions ([[MOVW]], [[RET]]).
A few instructions are enough to see how C maps to assembly:
\begin{verbatim}
  C code             ARM assembly (Asm5)
  ------             -------------------
  x = 1;             MOVW $1, R0
                     MOVW R0, x(SB)

  y = &x;            MOVW $x(SB), R0
                     MOVW R0, y(SB)

  z = x + y;         MOVW x+0(FP), R0
                     MOVW y+4(FP), R1
                     ADD  R1, R0
                     MOVW R0, z-4(SP)
\end{verbatim}
%
The \book{Assembler} explains the full instruction set and
addressing modes in detail.


\section{\plan design choices}

%yoann: caller-saved or callee-saved? what is design choice vs constraint? what is arch-specific?

%claude:
A compiler must make many decisions about how to use the
target machine's registers. Some of these are {\em hardware
constraints} imposed by the architecture (e.g., which register
is the program counter), and some are {\em design choices}
that the compiler or calling convention can decide freely
(e.g., which registers to use for passing arguments).
The most important design choice is the {\em calling convention}:
which registers are preserved across function calls and which
are not.

%claude:
In a {\em caller-saved} (``volatile'') convention, the caller
saves any registers it still needs before the call and restores
them after; the callee is free to clobber them.
In a {\em callee-saved} (``non-volatile'') convention, the callee
saves the registers it wants to use on entry and restores them
before returning; the caller can assume they are untouched.
In practice, architectures use a mix of both: some registers
are caller-saved and some are callee-saved.

%yoann: maybe diagram illustrating both cases, with function foo and bar and use of registers and comment indicating save/restore with maybe original C code and generated assembly to better understand
%claude:
\begin{verbatim}
  Caller-saved (R0-R3):            Callee-saved (R4-R11):

  foo:                             foo:
    MOVW $1, R0  // use R0           MOVW R4, -4(SP)  // save R4
    MOVW R0, -4(SP) // save R0      MOVW $1, R4      // use R4
    BL   bar                         BL   bar
    MOVW -4(SP), R0 // restore      // R4 still valid, no restore needed
    ...                              MOVW -4(SP), R4  // restore R4
                                     RET
\end{verbatim}
%claude:
With caller-saved registers, the caller must save and restore
around every call. With callee-saved registers, the callee
saves once on entry and restores once on exit, but only if
it actually uses the register. Functions that make no calls
(leaf functions) benefit most from callee-saved registers:
they can use them freely without saving.

%claude:
On ARM, the split between the two is fixed by the ARM
Procedure Call Standard (APCS): R0--R3 are caller-saved
(used for arguments and scratch) and R4--R11 are callee-saved.
This is a hardware constraint that [[5c]] must respect.
But within that framework, \plan makes its own
design choices: it reserves certain registers for fixed purposes
(R12 as the static base [[SB]], R13 as [[SP]], R14 as the link
register, R15 as [[PC]]), and it uses a leaf-function optimization
where functions that make no calls can skip saving callee-saved
registers entirely.


